{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"06155e70-51df-4e25-a2ca-d6375639a113","content":"For a .NET Web API project, use the `webapi` template:\n\n```bash\ndotnet new webapi -n MyApi\n```\n\n**Authentication options** (`--auth`):\n\n| Option | Description |\n|--------|-------------|\n| `None` | No authentication (default) |\n| `IndividualB2C` | Azure AD B2C individual accounts |\n| `SingleOrg` | Single tenant Azure AD |\n| `MultiOrg` | Multi-tenant Azure AD |\n| `Windows` | Windows authentication |\n\n**Example with auth:**\n```bash\ndotnet new webapi --auth SingleOrg --domain mydomain.onmicrosoft.com\n```\n\nYou can also add JWT Bearer auth manually via `Microsoft.AspNetCore.Authentication.JwtBearer` if you need custom token validation. Would you like help setting up a specific auth type?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"e624b639-d2ec-4d9e-b55d-d0359d7bd93a","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about web API project templates and authentication options. This is a general knowledge question about .NET (likely, given the repository context with dotnet plugins). I can answer this from my knowledge without needing to look at files.\n\nLet me provide a concise answer about dotnet web API templates and authentication options.","outputTokens":281,"requestId":"5001:1E3C:2735778:2B11643:69FBE1DC"},"id":"86e42034-1e8a-44f2-b13e-8227263cff41","timestamp":"2026-05-07T00:50:44.258Z","parentId":"1dac72bf-9865-46fb-a1ba-6a090ebf24e6"}
